Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 59th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Summer is over. Football is back. Onward.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by... Fundrise [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/936058f5-bb29-475c-869b-6020b707a85f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Venture capital has finally been democratized. You can now invest like the =
largest LPs in the world, gaining access to one of the best performing asse=
t classes of the last 20+ years.
Fundrise [ https://substack.com/redirect/936058f5-bb29-475c-869b-6020b707a8=
5f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is =
actively investing in some of the most prized private tech firms in the wor=
ld=E2=80=94including those leading the AI revolution.
This first-of-its-kind product has removed nearly all of the typical barrie=
rs that gatekeep VC by offering:
No accreditation required.=C2=A0
No 2-and-20 fees.
No membership fees.
The lowest venture investment minimum ever offered.=C2=A0
Join America=E2=80=99s largest direct-access alternative asset manager and =
the more than 2 million people already using Fundrise [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/936058f5-bb29-475c-869b-6020b707a85f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(1) Not Boring Founders: Crusoe Energy (Chase Lochmiller and Cully Cavness)=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/2489c0be-bc69-4f59-8cb6-9ca7405fbe7f?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy had the founders of Crusoe Energy on the pod. Crusoe is one of the mo=
st inventive and ambitious projects we=E2=80=99ve come across recently. The=
 company=E2=80=99s mission is to align the future of computing with the fut=
ure of the climate. How do they do that?
Crusoe taps into stranded energy =E2=80=94 methane being flared or excess p=
roduction from clean and renewable sources =E2=80=94 to power the compute r=
esources. Its initial focus was on bitcoin and crypto mining, but has recen=
tly focused in on building AI-specific cloud offerings.
For energy companies, Crusoe provides a new revenue stream and alternative =
to wasteful and environmentally-damaging flaring.=20
For clients, Crusoe is able to provide affordable compute resources by trad=
ing lower energy costs for a few extra milliseconds of latency, which matte=
rs much less for things like mining or training AI models than it does for =
normal internet stuff.=20
People are going to use more compute regardless. It=E2=80=99s inevitable an=
d it=E2=80=99s a good thing. Crusoe meets the demand for more data centers =
in a way that also reduces emissions. Abundance mindset. Capitalism at its =
finest.=20
(2) Frontier facilitates third round of carbon removal purchases [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/094bf310-9fec-4fce-97f1-c6f1ca3d59d0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Frontier has facilitated $7M of carbon removal purchases from 12 companies=
=E2=80=94Airhive, Alkali Earth, Banyu Carbon, Carbon Atlantis, CarbonBlue, =
CarbonRun, EDAC Labs, Holocene, Mati, Planetary Technologies, Spiritus Tech=
nologies, and Vaulted Deep=E2=80=94on behalf of buyers Stripe, Shopify, and=
 H&M Group.
We=E2=80=99ve covered Frontier a fair amount here at Not Boring. As a remin=
der, Frontier is an advance market commitment (AMC) to buy an initial $1B+ =
of permanent carbon removal between 2022 and 2030. It was founded by Stripe=
, Alphabet, Shopify, Meta, McKinsey and tens of thousands of businesses usi=
ng Stripe Climate.
The AMC announced its third round of carbon removal purchases, totaling $7M=
 across 12 companies. Notably, Frontier received 7x the number of applicati=
ons for the program this round versus its first batch in 2020 =E2=80=94 whi=
ch is kind of the point of the AMC. Pre-establish demand in order to pull-f=
orward supply. There=E2=80=99s still a long ways to go in terms of satisfyi=
ng that demand (only a small portion of the $1B commitment has been allocat=
ed), which leads us to believe we=E2=80=99ll see a wave of supply (carbon r=
emoval projects) come on-line in the next couple of years.
Joanna Klitzke [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d7c3cfd-2b67-4624-aa6a-9442=
738daf9c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] on the Frontier team published an awesome thread spotlighting the 12 com=
panies and their unique approaches to carbon removal, which you can checkou=
t here [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f7e308c-4778-416c-88f0-933f50043f8a=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(3) Japan launches 'moon sniper' lunar lander SLIM into space [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/370f77e3-1996-436f-b9df-38acb587ff46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Kantaro Komiya [ https://substack.com/redirect/44ce1194-30d2-4cbd-a1e7-5091=
55cac4c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for Reuters
Japan launched a lunar exploration spacecraft on Thursday aboard a homegrow=
n H-IIA rocket, hoping to become the world's fifth country to land on the m=
oon early next year.
Just two weeks after India became the fourth nation to successfully land on=
 the moon, Japan launched its own lunar-bound spacecraft. Beyond establishi=
ng Japan=E2=80=99s independent space capabilities, the expedition is meant =
to achieve a precise lunar landing =E2=80=94 meaning landing the spacecraft=
 at an exact location on the moon rather landing wherever it can. Once the =
craft lands, its mission is to test advanced optical and image processing t=
echnology, and then analyze some rock sites that could give insight into th=
e origins of the moon.
As the space race heats up, the moon has become a location of renewed inter=
est. There are limited resources on the moon, and countries are racing to s=
ecure those resources since they will eventually be needed to power further=
, deeper exploration.
Our friends at Pirate Wires [ https://substack.com/redirect/f696aee0-68e6-4=
be7-b218-a02d36aa04af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are going to need to hurry up if they want to make Moon a S=
tate.
(4) China Slowdown Means It May Never Overtake US Economy, Forecast Shows [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/56852a4b-c065-4654-aa5a-51744abba662?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jasmine Ng [ https://substack.com/redirect/ecaa4e3e-68ce-413c-a4e3-90bd2ca4=
7a23?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Bloomberg
China is no longer set to eclipse the US as the world=E2=80=99s biggest eco=
nomy soon, and it may never consistently pull ahead to claim the top spot a=
s the nation=E2=80=99s confidence slump becomes more entrenched.
China=E2=80=99s rise over the past 40 years has lifted nearly 800 million p=
eople out of poverty. That economic rise has done just about as much as any=
 other trend to increase global average quality of life standards during th=
e period. And its established China as the world=E2=80=99s second largest e=
conomy and, perhaps, the second most powerful nation.=20
But, hard times are ahead for China. It has an aging population, its export=
s are dropping, and its real estate market is plunging. It=E2=80=99s likely=
 heading into a recession, if not an economic depression.  These factors co=
mbined means that GDP growth will continue to slow, and according to Bloomb=
erg, slow to a rate at which China will not overtake the US=E2=80=99 econom=
y for nearly 20 years (if it ever does).
This isn=E2=80=99t just us cheering bad stuff happening to China =E2=80=94 =
as we mentioned at the top, an economically weak China likely means million=
s of more folks living in poverty. We=E2=80=99re not in the business of Sin=
o-schadenfreude. But China troubles are, in this case, most likely the U.S.=
=E2=80=99 treasures. China=E2=80=99s troubles could lead to reduced inflati=
on in the U.S. which would make lowering interest rates more tenable, which=
 would then boost an already-strong U.S. economic momentum. Noah Smith brok=
e it all down here [ https://substack.com/redirect/f0f2ac10-aad8-4a95-8110-=
98e841f637e9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ].
Whether or not an economically weaker China is a net-net =E2=80=9Cgood thin=
g=E2=80=9D is up for interpretation. Could it make China more likely to pro=
voke war? Could it weaken Xi=E2=80=99s/CCP=E2=80=99s grip on the population=
? Who are we to say. But, what we can say with some degree of certainty is =
that China=E2=80=99s economy is in a tough place while the US capitalist ma=
chine chugs along.
(5) Anduril Fury Launch [ https://substack.com/redirect/085c7c5b-6f07-4aff-=
9e14-4da3b6d82b9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
Ensuring that economic conflicts don=E2=80=99t overheat into wars is partia=
lly about deterrence. The U.S. doesn=E2=80=99t just have the best funded, m=
ost powerful military in the world to ensure that we can win any war, but a=
lso to prevent other nations from even attempting to start one. The militar=
y deters and defends.
And we do so, in part, by having the most advances military technologies an=
d defense systems. Not Boring Capital portfolio company, Anduril [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/ffd96155-78d9-42da-ab68-73b0d4bbfbe0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is arguably the most =
exciting defense company in the space right now =E2=80=94 having transforme=
d from sensors, to drones, to now a full fleet of land, air, and sea vehicl=
es.
On Thursday, Anduril founder Palmer Luckey announced that it had acquired B=
lue Force Technologies and unveiled its newest platform, Fury: a high-perfo=
rmance, multi-mission group 5 autonomous air vehicle, which is capable of p=
ulling 9Gs at Mach 0.95 for a tiny fraction of the cost of similarly perfor=
mant fighter craft. It=E2=80=99s unmanned, which means fewer human pilots i=
n harmed way.=20
Equipping the military with cutting-edge, affordable technology like Fury s=
hould only further deterrence and ensure economic wars stay economic.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

